@DATABASE
@WORDWRAP
@NODE MAIN
@TITLE "RETRO"
--------------- RETRO ---------------------


    @{"Introduction" link intro}

    @{"Requirements" link req}         @{"Me" LINK Edscape}

    @{"Intro Screen" link IntroScreen}         @{"Level Editor" LINK Editor}

    @{"Controls" link Controls}             @{"Levels" LINK Levels}

    @{"Weapons" link Weapons}              @{"Status Display" link Display}

    @{"Load & Save" link ls}          @{"Tool Types" Link tools}

    @{"Baddies" Link Baddies}              @{"Ships" Link Ships}

@ENDNODE

@NODE intro
@TITLE Introduction

  This Game is based on the old Spectrum game Thrust.

  From a side-on view you have to pilot a space-craft
  about a maze searching for the exit and destroying
  ground installations.

  Retro uses 16 colour Hi-res graphics , has 6 different ship's
  to fly and 8 different types of enemy ground installation.

  Each ship is equipped with a plasma gun , grenades and
  bombs and may be bought, repaired and re-equipped with
  credits gained from destroying enemy units.

  Their are 22 levels with a random gravity , atmospheric
  friction and enemy attributes making each game different.

  Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE req
@TITLE Requirements

  2MB Chip mem + 1 Fast mem

  @{b}It may be possible to run @{u}without fast memory@{uu} if a minimum workbench
  configuration is used.@{ub}

  Retro requires nearly 2MB of chip ram , so even with fast memory
  to run this game from a hard drive your workbench should be
  turned down to minimum. About 1930,000 bytes free should easily do.
  This is because the game uses hi-res 1920 x 768 double-buffered
  16 colour bitmaps.

  To run - Double click on the Retro game file.

  To Install - Simply drag the Retro drawer to required hard-drive location.


  It has been tested on -
                          A1200 + 4 M fast mem +hard drive +68882fpu

                          A1200 +hard drive + Blizzard 030 4M

  It can run from a hard or floppy drive.

  The Game Should contain the following files to work properly -

    Drawer or Disc called Retro - containing ~

                  @{b}Retro@{ub}      (file)- Game File (Double click to start)
                  @{b}Retro-Ed@{ub}   (file)- Level Designer
                  @{b}Retro.Guide@{ub} (file)- This File

                         @{b}GFX@{ub} (drawer) - containing 8 files

                           AdisSprites
                           Disshapes
                           introshapes
                           panel.pal
                           thrust.pal
                           thrusteditor.shapes
                           thrustintro
                           thrustshapes

                         @{b}Ships@{ub} (drawer) - containing 6 files

                          Delter.Shapes
                          Ray.Shapes
                          Fighter.Shapes
                          BullHead.Shapes
                          Bird_of_Pray.Shapes
                          Rocket.Shapes

                         @{b}SaveGame@{ub} (drawer) - containing 1 or 0 files

                          may contain Retro.save file

                         @{b}Sounds@{ub} (drawer) - containing 9 files

                          boom
                          click
                          clonk
                          clunk
                          MyFire1
                          MyFire2
                          MyFire3
                          MyFire4
                          Thrusters

                         @{b}Levels@{ub} (drawer) - containing 21 files

                          21 * Retro@{i}level-number@{ui}.Dat

  The level editor requires the speech library and translator devices.

  Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE IntroScreen "Intro Screen"

    Upon loading Retro you will see the @{"intro screen." LINK GFX/thrustintro/main}

    This screen appears before starting a new level or
    after you have had a ship destroyed.

    Moving the joystick in the game port will move a red circular
    pointer next to the various game options.

    To play the game press fire with the pointer next to @{"GO" LINK controls}.
    @{i}This is the default setting.@{ui}

    The other options are -  @{b}Restart@{ub} - reset game.
                            @{b}QUIT@{ub} - back to Workbench.

                            ---------------------------------

                            @{b}Repair Damage@{ub}
                               20˘ repairs 15 points of armour
                               for the currently selected ship.
                            @{i}Looks like a medical box@{ui}

                            @{b}Load@{ub} -@{"Load" LINK ls} the save game
                            specified in the @{tool-types. LINK Tools}
                            @{i}Default = levels/retro.save@{ui}

                            @{b}Save@{ub} -@{"Save" LINK ls} the save game
                            specified in the @{tool-types. LINK Tools}

                            @{b}Cheat@{ub} -
                              Advances one level - and gives
                              you 400 credits.

                            -----------------------------------

                            @{b}Buy Weapons@{ub}
                              Buy for currently selected ship -

                                @{"Plasma" LINK weapons} 2˘=10 bullets
                                @{"Grenades" LINK weapons} 15˘ each
                                @{"Bomb" LINK weapons} 30˘ each

                              up to the ships maximum storage
                              capacity for each weapon type.

                            -----------------------------------
                            @{b}Buy or Select Ship@{ub}
                            @{i}Pictures and names of the six ships@{ui}

                            click once to buy a @{"ship" LINK ships}
                            (a green tick appears in a box near-by.)

                            click again to select the ship.
                            a small dot moves next to the selected
                            ship.

Also displayed on the intro screen is the current level to play
@{i}arrow pointing to level number@{ui}.

@{Gravity,friction LINK grav},@{credits LINK Credits}
and selected ships three ammo levels for above weapons.
@{i}all showing as level bars@{ui}.

Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Controls

Once GO is selected you will enter the level.
The game is initially paused until the joystick button is pressed.

        Joystick (Game Port)

                  Fire Weapon @{i}press up@{ui}

                       |
               Spin  --o--  Spin
                       |

                 Change Weapon @{i}cycle @{"-->plasma->grenades->bombs->" LINK 
Weapons}@{ui}

      @{B}Fire Button@{ub}--Thrust



A weapon will only fire at certain rates- after using a bomb
you will not be able to fire again for a few seconds.

The Craft will accelerate to top speed if the fire button is
held down. Upon release the engine stops and you will have
to accelerate from zero again.

The currently selected weapon is displayed in a box in the
middle of the ships @{"status display" LINK display} at the bottom of the
screen.

Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Weapons

  Each ship has various maximum amounts of the same 3 weapons -

    @{b}Plasma@{ub} - a rapid rate short range front gun  (1 point of damage)
             @{i}weightless- never effected by gravity.
                 little recoil@{ui}

    @{b}Grenades@{ub} - a medium rate long range front missile  (7 points of damage)
             @{i}heavy- effected by gravity.
                 medium recoil@{ui}

    @{b}Bombs@{ub} - a low rate very long range rear missile  (20 points of damage)
             @{i}very heavy- highly effected by gravity.
                 large recoil@{ui}

    Your currently selected ship displays weapon status on the
    @{"ship status display" LINK display} during play or as three
    level bars on the @{"intro screen" LINK introscreen}.

    Level bars and pick-ups are coded with -

        Yellow ball  -- Plasma -- pick-ups give up to 10 balls

        Purple Disc  -- Grenades -- pick-ups up to give 5

        3 Blue tubes -- Bombs --- pick-ups up to give 3

        White with red cross --- Repairs --- Heal up to 25 hull strength

    Any ammo or repairs from a pick-up over your ships maximum
    for that weapon type is wasted upon collection.

    ---------------------------------------------------------------

    You can also damage the enemy by --

     # Blasting them with your jet - @{i}acts like a very short
       range plasma gun with a wide spread and unlimited ammo
       pointing backwards.@{ui}

     # Colliding with them - @{i}does equal damage to your ship
       1-8 points depending on your speed.@{ui}

     # Shooting each other - @{i}all enemy shots can damage other
       enemy installations including themselves if the bullet rebounds.
       The only exception are Volcano base bullets, grenades and bombs
       do not damage Volcano bases. This is to stop them wiping
       themselves out from rebounds.@{ui}


Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Display

  While playing a level a status panel appears at the bottom of
  the play area. these relate to -

  DAMAGE -- Level bar shows amount of damage the ship can sustain.

  WEAPON  -- In the box is a picture representing the currently used
             weapon.

  Next a level bar shows amount of plasma, then grenades are represented
  as egg shaped graphics and finally bombs, represented as larger images
  that supposed to be bomb shaped.

Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE ls "Load & Save"

  Pressing fire on these options loads or saves your game status.
  upon pressing you here two beeps, after the second beep the save
  is complete.

  Note - only one save game file is supported so subsequent saving
  saves over the last savegame file.

  By changing the @{"tool type" link tools} on the retro icon, saving can be redirected
  to another file or place.

Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE tools "Tool Types"

  Retro's icon has 2 tool types -

   LoadPath -- Points to which group of game levels to play.
               Used to switch to a hole new group of up to
               21 levels.

   SaveFile -- Path & name of file to save to. So more than one
               game may be stored.

  --------------------------------------------------------------

  Retro-Ed's icon also has two tool types -

   LoadPath -- as above.

   PreLoad -- Points to the specific level to load upon loading
              the editor in the loadpaths level set.

Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}    Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Baddies
  Enemy installations take the form of -

      *     @{b}Turret@{ub} --- Fire standard bullets more or less directly at
            the players position doing 3 points of damage.
            A turret has an average of 7 hit points and thus cannot
            usually survive a single grenade.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Purple sphere with blue window.

            @{i}Value 1 credit@{ui}

      *     @{b}Launcher@{ub} --- Shoot Guided Missiles doing 10 points of
            damage. Their guidance systems vary and their hit points
            average 11.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Green rectangles sandwich a blue 
window.
            @{i}Value 10 credits@{ui}

      *     @{b}Repulser@{ub} --- Repulser's do no damage to the player unless
            they smash them against a solid object causing collision
            damage.

            Their effect is to push the player away from them whenever the
            player gets within range.

            They have an average of 35 hit points.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Grey sphere.

            @{i}Value 5 credits@{ui}

      *     @{b}Attractor@{ub} --- Attractor's do no damage to the player unless
            they smash them against a solid object causing collision
            damage.

            Their effect is to pull the player towards them whenever the
            player gets within range.

            They have an average of 15 hit points.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Grey dome on a rectangular base.

            @{i}Value 5 credits@{ui}

      *     @{b}Volcano Base@{ub} --- These are 3 times as long as previous
            enemy and are thus easy to hit. They fire a variety of bullet's
            , grenades and bombs at random whenever the player is spotted.
            Damage ranges from 1 to 20 hit point's.
            These tend to take out any damageable object within range
            except Volcano bases which are immune to theirs and
            other Volcano base weapons.
            Collisions will burn 5 times more than purple walls
            destroying your craft in seconds.

            They are very tough having an average of 100 hit point's.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Big Brown , yellow and orange.

            @{i}Value 60 credits@{ui}

      *     @{b}Spinner@{ub} --- Spinner's do no damage to the player,
            instead they randomly turn the player clockwise or
            anti-clockwise. This effect makes it difficult to manoeuvre and
            is increased the more Spinner's can see the player.

            They have an average of 12 hit point's.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Radar antenna on a yellow base.

            @{i}Value 8 credits@{ui}

     *      @{b}Random Attack Base@{ub} --- These are the worst enemy
            installations in the game. Their only weak point is their
            size which is twice as big as normal turrets , making them
            mush easier to hit. Collision will burn like purple walls.

            They attack with one of 7 attacks --

            1) A normal bullet doing 5 points of damage shot at the
            player.

            2) A grenade doing 14 points of damage shot vaguely in the
            players direction.

            3) A guided missile doing 10 points of damage.

            4) A slow rocket (@{i}like a bomb only slower and not affected
            by gravity.@{ui}) Easily avoided but lasts a long time and
            does 25 points of damage.

            5)/6) Pull & push the player like an Attractor/Repuluser.

            7) Spin like a spinner by 15 degrees.

            They have an average of 120 hit point's.
            @{i}Description@{ui} - Yellow and orange dome.
            @{i}Value 100 credits@{ui}


       Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Ships
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
| Name  |  Acceleration | HS | Max Speed | Plasma | Grenades | Bombs |  $  |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Delta  |      50%      | 50 |   50%     |  100   |     5    |   2   | 100 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Ray    |      70%      | 60 |   40%     |  200   |    10    |   1   | 150 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Fighter|     100%      | 43 |  100%     |  130   |     3    |   1   |  75 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Bull   |      40%      | 75 |   40%     |  400   |    14    |   5   | 200 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Bird   |      60%      | 85 |   60%     |  300   |    12    |   4   | 300 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+
|Rocket |      80%      |100 |   80%     |  400   |    18    |   8   | 400 |
+-------+---------------+----+-----------+--------+----------+-------+-----+

HS - Hull Strength - Amount of damage sustainable.

Other differences --

  The @{b}Fighter@{ub} has a very rapid weapons but suffers from 
increased
  recoil when using grenades.

  The @{b}Bullhead@{ub} has reduced recoil from grenades and bombs.

  The @{b}Bird of pray@{ub} has a slightly more rapid fire plasma gun
  and very rapid fire bombs.

  The @{b}Rocket@{ub} has increased rate of firing of bombs and 
grenades  and reduced recoil from bombs.

    Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Levels

    Upon the levels you will find -

      @{"Walls" LINK Walls}

      @{Pick-ups LINK Weapons}

      @{"Background" LINK Background}

      @{"Doors & Switches" LINK Doors}

      @{"Barrels" LINK barrels}

      @{"Enemy installations" LINK Baddies}

      @{"Exits" LINK Exits}

        If your ship is destroyed the game is over unless you have
        or are able to buy another ship.
        When you re-enter the level with your new ship any enemy
        destroyed the previous attempts will remain destroyed and
        any pick-ups used are not replenished.
        Destroyed barrels & doors are not replaced but all switches
        are renewed.

    Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Walls

  Their are three types of wall - all are invulnerable.

    @{b}Blue Walls@{ub} -

      This is a standard wall , it does 0 to 8 points of damage
      depending on your speed upon collision. Any projectiles hitting
      this type of wall ricochet away although their life span will
      be depleted.

      If your ship hits it will also rebound off at reduced speed
      due to friction.

    @{b}Green Walls@{ub} -

      Springy walls.

      As blue except green walls do no damage no matter what speed
      you are doing. Also a bullets life span is not depleted.

      When your ship hits a green wall it will rebound faster than
      before collision.

    @{b}Purple Walls@{ub} -

      This is a hot wall , it does 0 to 8 points of damage as blue
      and a additional 1 point of damage per 50th of a second while
      contact remains.

      All projectiles die upon contact and your ship will be
      greatly slowed by friction.

      Back to @{"Levels" link Levels}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Background

  Stars,planets,girders,orange pipes and grey walls are all 
background.
  They do not have any effect on the game and may be flown over safely.

    Back to @{"Levels" link Levels}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Doors "Doors & Switches"
    Doors appear as yellow and orange striped rectangles.

    They cannot be harmed by the jet or plasma weapon and take
    100 points of damage from all others until destroyed.

    Switches appear as light bulbs on a grey base.

    They are activated by collision with your ship or when hit by
    weapon fire.
    They operate a particular door which will open if not already
    open or destroyed.
    When a switch activates the light-bulb light up orange.

    Once activated a door will remain open for a preset time and
    then close, the switch that operated it will reset.

    If caught in a closing door your ship will be pushed out and
    take 20 points of damage.

  Back to @{"Levels" link Levels}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Barrels

    Barrels look like large orange squares.
    They block your movement and  absorb weapon fire but
    otherwise have no effect on the game.

    They take about 12 points of damage.

        Back to @{"Levels" link Levels}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Exits

    Exits are purple with `Exit' written across them.

    Fly into these to end the level.

Back to @{"Levels" link Levels}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Editor "The Level Editor"

     @{"Hot Keys" LINK hot}

     @{"Level Display" LINK ldisplay}

     @{"Buttons" LINK Buttons}

     @{"Foreground/Background slider gadgets" LINK sliders}

     @{"Big Objects" LINK big}

     @{"Map" LINK map}

     @{"Walls" LINK w}

     @{"Doors" LINK d}

     @{"Switches" LINK s}

     @{"Tool Types" Link tools}

     To @{b}QUIT@{ub} hold both mouse buttons down.

     Back to @{"Contents" link MAIN}
@ENDNODE

@NODE hot "Hot Keys"

  @{b}Curser Keys@{ub}   --->  Scroll View position.


  @{b}Numeric Keypad@{ub}

        7   ---->  Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget up one.

        1   ---->  Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget down one.


        8   ---->  Background @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget up one.

        2   ---->  Background @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget down one.


@{b}Keyboard@{ub}

  Del  ---> Move Background @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to blank space.

  b    ---> Move Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to first blue wall.

  g    ---> Move Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to first green wall.

  r    ---> Move Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to first purple wall.
            @{i}(red wall)@{ui}

  o    ---> Move Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to turret.
            @{i}(first object)@{ui}

  p    ---> Move Foreground @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget to plasma
            @{i}(first)@{ui} pick-up.


    Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE ldisplay "Level Display"

     The Large window in the top left of the display shows a
     section of the currently loaded level.

     The section shown can be changed by either using the cursor keys,
     the @{"map" LINK map} or via a joystick in the game port.

     The mouse clicked in this area will make a change to the level.

        Left click -- Changes the foreground graphics of the square
                      beneath the mouse pointer.
                      Graphics is changed to whatever the foreground
                      @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget points to.

        Right click -- Changes the background graphics of the square
                       beneath the mouse pointer.
                       Graphics is changed to whatever the background
                       @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget points to.

       Each square can contain 1 foreground and 1 background
       graphics. The foreground is blitted over the background.

       The blank space on the background @{"slider" LINK sliders} gadget
       rubs out both foreground and background graphics.

       Some of the foreground graphics are reduced to one graphics
       for the editor and may look different in the game.
       @{i}e.g only the upward facing repulsers graphics are in the
       editor. The game will change this to the facing graphics it
       thinks is best.@{ui}

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Buttons

      @{b}Load@{ub}
                     Brings a requester up to select a new level
                     to load.
      @{u}                                                          @{uu}

      @{b}Save@{ub}
                     Saves the current level to ram:.
                     The level will be named the same name as
                     the last loaded level.

                     A prompt will ask if you wish to change
                     @{"door" LINK d} and them @{"switch" LINK s} information.
                     Press y or n to select.

                     The level takes a few seconds to save.
                     The computer says `finished' when done
                     and the mouse pointer re-activates.

                     @{b}Don't forget to copy your work to disk
                     after quitting the editor and changing the
                     number in the file name if necessary.
      @{u}                                                          @{uu}

      @{b}Clear@{ub}
                     Removes all graphics except the border
                     wall tiles blanking the level.
      @{u}                                                          @{uu}

      @{b}Auto@{ub}
                     Tries to fill any missing @{"wall" LINK w} tiles.
                     May take a few seconds.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE sliders "Foreground/Background slider gadgets"

   Next to the buttons, below the map are for want of a better
   name what I call slider gadgets.
   The left one contains foreground graphics and the right one
   background.

   An arrow points to the centre graphics on both sliders.
   This indicates the current tile to be placed upon the
   level display via the mouse.

   You can change this graphics using either the @{"keyboard" LINK hot}
   or the mouse. @{i}Clicking on the graphics within the slider to
   re-centre the slider upon this graphics.@{ui}

   @{bg shine}Foreground Slider@{bg back}

      Contains--- Blue @{"walls" LINK w} 9 tiles

                  Green @{"walls" LINK w} 9 tiles

                  Purple @{"walls" LINK w} 9 tiles

                  Objects - Turret, Launcher, Barrel, Repulser,
                            Attractor, Volcano Base, Spinner, Exit,
                            Random Attack Base, Switch, Door.

                  Pick-ups - 4 tiles

                  Player Start Position

                  @{i}Only one player start position will appear
                  if used again the previous one will disappear.@{ui}


   @{bg shine}Background Slider@{bg back}

                 @{b}Blank Space@{ub} - the initial setting rubs
                 background and foreground graphics off any RMB
                 clicked square.

                 The other tiles are just to make the levels look
                 more interesting.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE big "Big objects"

   Volcano Bases and Random Attack Bases are longer than 1 tile.

    To place a Volcano base on the level place 3 of the tile
    representing the base next to each other horizontally.
    The game will sort out the proper graphics.

    Volcano Bases should only be placed on top of a solid floor.


    For Random Attack Bases place 2 tiles similar to Volcano
    Bases.
    These bases may be placed anywhere but must be horizontal.

    Load level 13 as an example of how they look in the
    editor. It has a volcano base on the middle floor and
    Two Random Attack Bases on the lower floor.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Map

Clicking on the map.

   The map in the top right corner only shows part of the
   level. To scroll the map click the right mouse button
   to where you wish to re-centre to on the map.

   The left mouse button scrolls the level display without
   scrolling the map.

    The map scrolls automatically if the cursor keys or joystick
    is used.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}

@ENDNODE

@NODE w "Walls"

     Each of the 3 wall types has 9 tiles.

     These walls only allow collision in one particular
     direction and therefore walls must be protected by
     other walls of the correct type to stop the player
     flying throw them.

     For each wall type the tiles are arranged as such --

        Floor type ---- Always bonuses player upwards.

        Ceiling type ---- Always bonuses player downwards.

        Left-Wall type ---- Always bonuses player to the right.

        Right-Wall type ---- Always bonuses player to the left.

        The next four fill the diagonal gaps between horizontal
        and vertical wall sections.@{i} The correct one still
        must be used.@{ui}

        The last is to fill large sections of levels and should not
        come into contact with the player.@{i}except the very corners
        of the tile @{i}as in the border.@{ui}

  To help pick the correct wall face the auto button may be used.
  It will attempt to place the proper wall types next to any already
  on the level. It doesn't always pick the best one but the level
  will be usable.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE d "Doors"

     Upon saving you are asked if you wish to change door
     information.
     This allows you to change the amount of time a door
     stays open.

     If you press y for yes the display will centre on the first
     door which will be marked with a orange pipe.

     Pressing 0 to 9 will assign a time for the door to remain
     open once operated as follows-

     The door will stay open for approximately 2 seconds * the
     number you pressed.

     pressing 0 results in the door opening for a very long
     time.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE s "switches"

     After door information you are asked if you wish
     to change switch information.
     This allows you to assign which door the switch operates.
     Pressing from 1 to 5 assigns that door to the switch high-lighted.
     The doors are numbered highest-left to lowest right.

     Pressing 0 for a switch assigns the switch to either door 1 or 2
     every time the level is entered.

Back to @{"The Level Editor" LINK Editor}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EdScape "Me"
Retro - Copyright (c) 1999, Stephen Strickland.

      I have written one other game @{bg shine}@{u}EdScape@{uu}@{bg back} ,a loona-lander
      style game available from Online Pd.

      Retro is 100% Blitz Basic 2.1 and all of the graphics were done
      in DPaintIV except the ships for witch I wrote a hi-res vector
      revolving program.

      Levels 18+ by Jonathan Strickland

@ENDNODE
